\title{pgeeVar: Penalized GEE Variance Estimation Tools for Binary Longitudinal Data}
\description{
\code{pgeeVar} provides the current numerical core for the \code{pgee-variance}
methods project. It supplies low-level simulation, fitting, and
variance-estimation tools for clustered binary longitudinal data.
}
\details{
The current public API is centered on three tasks:
\itemize{
\item generating correlated binary longitudinal data with
\code{\link[=simulate_correlated_binary_data]{simulate_correlated_binary_data()}}
\item fitting penalized generalized estimating equation models with \code{\link[=pgee]{pgee()}}
\item computing the supported small-sample covariance estimators with
\code{\link[=compute_pgee_variances]{compute_pgee_variances()}}
}

To inspect the supported estimator set, use \code{\link[=available_estimators]{available_estimators()}} or
\code{\link[=available_estimator_names]{available_estimator_names()}}. The package is intentionally focused on the
manuscript's 14-estimator variance-comparison workflow.
}
\section{Current package stage}{

The package now exposes both user-facing wrappers and lower-level engines.
\code{\link[=simulate_correlated_binary_data]{simulate_correlated_binary_data()}} and \code{\link[=pgee]{pgee()}} are the main entry points,
while \code{\link[=dgp_generate]{dgp_generate()}} and \code{\link[=pgee_fit]{pgee_fit()}} remain available for advanced users
who need the lower-level workflow.
}

